title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>In a 2-category, interchange is strict; in particular, this means that vertical composition and horizontal composition commute strictly with each other. This is very useful for <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00B8.xml"
addr="jms-00B8"
title="String diagrams">string diagrams</fr:link>, but it is not strictly necessary. In a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00B8.xml"
addr="jms-00B8"
title="String diagrams">string diagram</fr:link>, strict interchange means that 2-cells can be freely moved upward and downward; so if you want to use diagrammatic reasoning to study something in a structure that has only weak interchange, you need two things:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>The vertical position of a 2-cell is fixed.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>No two 2-cells should appear at the same vertical position.</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>To move a 2-cell up or down is to insert an interchange cell. It is this principle that makes <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00BG.xml"
addr="jms-00BG"
title="Homotopy.io"><fr:code>homotopy.io</fr:code></fr:link> work.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>